Hydrogen bonds, which occur when a hydrogen atom covalently bonded to an electronegative atom (such as oxygen or nitrogen) interacts with another electronegative atom, provide directionality and specificity to host-guest recognition. They help align the host and guest molecules in precise orientations, enhancing selectivity and binding strength. Anion-π interactions, which involve the attraction between an anion and the electron-deficient π-system of an aromatic ring, are increasingly recognized as important contributors to the stabilization of supramolecular complexes, especially when the guest is an anionic species. These interactions can complement hydrogen bonding by providing additional binding sites and modulating the overall affinity and selectivity of the host for its guest. Together, these non-covalent forces enable the reversible, yet robust, assembly of complex architectures characteristic of supramolecular chemistry, allowing for dynamic behavior, molecular Hydrogen bonds, which occur when a hydrogen atom covalently bonded to an electronegative atom (such as oxygen or nitrogen) interacts with another electronegative atom, provide directionality and specificity to host-guest recognition. They help align the host and guest molecules in precise orientations, enhancing selectivity and binding strength. Anion-π interactions, which involve the attraction between an anion and the electron-deficient π-system of an aromatic ring, are increasingly recognized as important contributors to the stabilization of supramolecular complexes, especially when the guest is an anionic species. These interactions can complement hydrogen bonding by providing additional binding sites and modulating the overall affinity and selectivity of the host for its guest. Together, these non-covalent forces enable the reversible, yet robust, assembly of complex architectures characteristic of supramolecular chemistry, allowing for dynamic behavior, molecular Hydrogen bonds, which occur when a hydrogen atom covalently bonded to an electronegative atom (such as oxygen or nitrogen) interacts with another electronegative atom, provide directionality and specificity to host-guest recognition. They help align the host and guest molecules in precise orientations, enhancing selectivity and binding strength. Anion-π interactions, which involve the attraction between an anion and the electron-deficient π-system of an aromatic ring, are increasingly recognized as important contributors to the stabilization of supramolecular complexes, especially when the guest is an anionic species. These interactions can complement hydrogen bonding by providing additional binding sites and modulating the overall affinity and selectivity of the host for its guest. Hydrogen bonds, which occur when a hydrogen atom covalently bonded to an electronegative atom (such as oxygen or nitrogen) interacts with another electronegative atom, provide directionality and specificity to host-guest recognition. They help align the host and guest molecules in precise orientations, enhancing selectivity and binding strength. Anion-π interactions, which involve the attraction between an anion and the electron-deficient π-system of an aromatic ring, are increasingly recognized as important contributors to the stabilization of supramolecular complexes, especially when the guest is an anionic species. These interactions can complement hydrogen bonding by providing additional binding sites and modulating the overall affinity and selectivity of the host for its guest. Together, these non-covalent forces enable the reversible, yet robust, assembly of complex architectures characteristic of supramolecular chemistry, allowing for dynamic behavior, molecular recognition, and functional properties such as catalysis, sensing, and molecular transport.', 'key_concepts': ['Non-covalent interaction', 'Hydrogen bond', 'Anion-π interaction', 'Supramolecular
